Yes. And - but in the war - I had a - two pigs - because we moved, when father - retired he had to give up the house, you see, you lived on the - was
n't the - you know, you were - had to move. We went to a house at top of Bellmont Hill and then Squire Smith at Shawcros, Harry Smith - he was - got into money difficulties and - the rent was only three pound ten a year so you're not surprised at him gett
ing into money difficulties. And - he sold I think it was thirty-eight cottages or more - all his property in the village, 'cos he had to put part of it up because it was entail for his son, he was crippled with }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
