d - we lived in Waldon at first, 'cos the - and - we - I - farm - a man named Eton bought the house at the top of Bellmont Hill, you see it was very difficult to learn my mother a house being blind and we got - and I - tried to buy it, I got a man - I wen
t
 to the building society and asked if he could lend me a little money 'cos property was cheap that time of day and he said he would. I never said a word to anybody - and - I suppose I had it out with 'em and telling 'em all the while and they kept running
 
it up. And this Mr Freeman said, it'll go a hundred and twenty but no more. Well that made it a hundred and twenty five. And after - the sale this old farmer - who wasn't no cop come up to me and said you can have your house at my price, I said, thank you
 
we don't want it. Wouldn't have anything to do with him. And Mr Barnard, he was another farmer at the other big farm, he said, well don't worry, he said - if I've got a house you can have one, but then he hadn't got any empty. I was very worried. Me broth
e
r, he what lives up Wickham Road, he went in to the White Horse in the evening, and the man at the White Horse said - how did you get on? Oh, he said, didn't get anywhere. Well he said, there's a toll bar for sale. He said, go and talk it over with your s
i
ster - he said, and if - you like to go in to Waldon tomorrow morning - and - see to it, he said - I won't go, but if you don't I shall buy it. Well that's the house with the ball on down there, the toll bridge. But that was - I suppose - you see, I had t
h
at catalogue and there was a dispute about a right of way and I lent it to a person in Newport and the lawyers never give me that back, there was all the price of the house, that house which they run up a hundred and twenty-five pound which I tried to buy
 
was only valued seventy-five. 'Cos the roof was bad, so - it was a good thing they did - put it up, 'cos this - old - Eton sold it to a - a Major Berkley, and after he got it he said - he went to a bookseller in Waldon he said, I'm soon going to turn the 
Reynolds's out of the cottages, the bookseller told me, he was a friend, I said, well you can tell him from me he ought to be ashamed of himself I said, a blind woman.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6762071 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 So where did you go in the end then?
\par 
