Oh yes, he was a - yes, I always got on very well with me brothers but I had a nice doll, they would break a doll if I had one, you know what boys are. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6762071 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 Was there one brother you got on particularly
 well with or did you get on equally well with them all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16153212 MR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 
Well I got on well with all of 'em but I was so fond of me brother Richard and Ted.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6762071 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 The younger ones?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16153212 MR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6773215\charrsid8475667 
Yes, but he was a wonderful one my brother Richard, he was a - ALA warden in the
 war, you know, he had cancer of the lung, and Mrs Carmen took him up to London to see Sir Winston Churchill's - position and shook his head and Mrs Carmen - the specialist told Mrs Coleman, she said, well if I - you had a son wouldn't you try so she had 
him up to London but of course they couldn't do anything they just had him in and bucked him up. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 
And he was a wonderful man, he's - he was one of these service at the church and - when he died I was - they couldn't get that on his small church, there was a 
lot at the funeral. He was a wonderful - wonderful close to - well all me brothers turned out wonderfully well, every one of them did. I must say that.
