Oh yes, I'm always regular. Oh yes, my mother was very religious woman. And I mean that was an awful thing to go blind with a young family like that but she never complained. No, she was wonderful with all of us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6762071 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 
Did she have many visitors, did the parson come and visit her and that sort of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16153212 MR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 
Oh yes, but you see - she'd been blind I should think - thirty years or more before anybody ever come
, and then there was a - quite that, and then there was a Mrs Barthrop - came once a year, she lived in a big house up the road on Major Bartlett's farm what bought our - and she said she'd been asked by the county council to come and see if mother was lo
o
ked after, she come once a year. Well then - after that - the year - two or three years we had a visitor to the blind, a blind man come And then - we had - a woman come, and the last come Miss Reece and I still hear from her. Mother died in '37, and they 
a
llowed mother a little pension so things was a bit easier 'cos when me father died we only had twelve shillings a week coming in. And so of course I took in washing and that and needlework, and - they give mother a blind - a blind pension so that helped s
o things was more }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6773215\charrsid8475667 comfortable}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 
 and that Miss Reece used to come and take me for a drive, I was just about worn out, every night I used to - morning four o'clock I used to get up, put some milk in a flask and - come down and - I used to say, you awake mother?
 And she'd say, oh Meg I wish you wouldn't do it. I said, do what mother? She said, come down - like this. I said, well I shall. Then she'd go off to sleep again. But you never see such a dreadful place, it ate all her breast away, every bit. She used to 
have haemorrhage. I used to have to give her a morphi}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6773215\charrsid8475667 ne}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 
 tablet and push the bed up and of course - I used to have to - I have washed on a Sunday that's the only times 'cos -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16153212 MR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 
They were all very friendly and - one thing, always ready to do anything - for each other then. No one ever thought of - of - getting anybody in to do the washing when - a baby was born or anything, a neighbour always done it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6762071 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 
Do you remember what happened when your youngest brother was born, how your mother managed with the house?
