I think my sister must have been at home, I don't remember a lot of - well I do remember him being born, but - of course - no children then ever knew a mother was going to have a baby. No. It was all secret. Do you know such a thing was never 
mentioned. Oh no. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6762071 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 Was it a surprise then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16153212 MR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 
Yes, I mean I didn't know anything about it - and - I think - I don't think - I think my sister must have told me - before she - but she - I didn't have a lot to do with my sister because you see she
 was eight years older than me, and she - left school, she went with a farmer and his wife at Wickham to look after her child - her children. And so she was out as I grew up. But - I never had a lot of - only the school companions you see 'cos mine was al
l brothers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6762071 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 But you'd have school friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16153212 MR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 
Oh very nice yes. I believe they're all dead now as far as I can find out. They had one or two die this year, but - we - I had a - after Miss Crane our Sunday schoolteacher give up we had a Miss Waterhou
se, our teacher, and then - her father was headmaster of the new school when they was building, that was built about 1876. And - she continued and she - oh I used to - all for that. We all had a frock on and - and a nice clean pinafore and we used to have
 
a wonderful evening. Then all of a sudden she give we girls up and took on - and took up boys. Well then after she - she went to train as a nurse and during the first world war she was in the - Queens Nursing Service abroad, and then - and she used to tal
k, but she - she never got up no more. And then she fell and broke her leg you know and that was the end of her, she wouldn't - she was eighty-nine.
