 to get out to service together while they were getting married so I come over and took home - over when I was eighteen. And that's so - but - I had a very happy time though the matron was an old hussy Oh yes, she used to have - a - every other Sunday - m
o
rning, the other one afternoon and evening, of course used to have to walk to Newport, and - if I - I had to report when I got in, she'd say - she couldn't call me Margaret she said too long a name and - called me Anne, she'd say, Anne, it's one minute pa
st nine I had to call her at half past six in the morning, cup of tea and can of hot water and if I was a minute over she'd tell me. Oh she was an old tartar, oh she was an old driver.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6762071 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 She was after you was she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16153212 MR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 Oh terror. Yes. But still I -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6762071 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 Were you sort of employed by her or were you paid by the hospital?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16153212 MR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 I was paid by the hospital, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6762071 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 But you waited on her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16153212 MR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 
Oh yes, I - and answered the door you see, the front door and all like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6762071 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 To callers you mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16153212 MR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 Oh yes, to all the callers, oh yes. I enjoyed being there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6762071 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 Tell me what else you had to do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16153212 MR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 
Well I had to do a lot of linen work, mend all the sheets, used to have to go in the - a small room at three o'clock every afternoon put great patches on sheets and my eyes was bad, I had to - doctor said I hadn't got to do so much. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6762071 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 Did you have to do out a lot of rooms every day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16153212 MR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 
Oh I had to do her sitting room, and all the long corridor, that had a long corridor from end to end, sweep 'em and
 - and dust that and - and the dispenser slept there in case they wanted anything during the night and I had to - put his hot water and put him a glass of milk and bread and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6773215\charrsid8475667 cheese}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667  in his bedroom of a night and - and I had to do her bedroom, my bedroom, I 
had plenty to do, we had to work hard.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6762071 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 Did you have to do front steps and whiten steps and those kinds of thing?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16153212 MR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 
Well they wasn't whitened but I had to do the steps and the hall had got - these tiles, I had to wash them over every day, and - oh yes, there was plenty to do, and then - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6773215\charrsid8475667 occasionally}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667  if they wanted any help I'd go up and help in the ward, well I liked the life.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6762071 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 Did you have any time off during the day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16153212 MR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 No, oh no, no, we hadn't time off then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6762071 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 What time did you finish in the evening?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16153212 MR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 
Well we was done at teatime and then we had - we used to sit in the kitchen with }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6773215\charrsid8475667 needlework}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667  and - and - then we used to have to - take her hot milk and that and then had to go to bed, about - ten I think, half past nine or ten, we had to get up very early.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6762071 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 When you sat in the kitchen who did you sit with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16153212 MR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 Oh all the servants, there was the laundry maids, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6773215\charrsid8475667 cook}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 
 and laundry maids, cook and kitchen maid and - all the maids used to come down sometimes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6762071 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 That was for the whole hospital?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16153212 MR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 
Yes, see that was a - but they don't have so many patients in now I don't think but they don't have so many wards open, they're short of beds.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6762071 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 How did you get on with the other people there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16153212 MR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 Oh very well. I always got on with people. Yes I did, mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6762071 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 Did you feel that she was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6773215\charrsid8475667 interested}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667  in you as a person or did she just think of you as a servant the matron do you think?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16153212 MR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 
Oh I don't know, she was variable. When I took the cooking on she gave me a Mrs Beaton's book which w
as just out then. Well that's another thing I've lost Can't find it nowhere. We had a woman speak at our institute, try and find the that's worth a good deal of money. 'Cos that - I think was an early edition. But of course that's - that's - you can - sam
e as - is now - things so dear you couldn't cook, I mean nothing to make anything of six eggs in there you know, very - have you ever read one? Don't you think it's extravagant.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6762071 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 Tell me more about when you worked in the hospital, when you went out in t
he evening did you have to be back at a certain time?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16153212 MR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 Nine o'clock, and then we had to be no more after nine.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6762071 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 
Did she - what - did she sort of talk to you and ask you say how your mother was and take an interest in you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16153212 MR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 No, no she wasn't that type. She -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6762071 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 She wasn't interested in your home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16153212 MR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 No, no, no she wasn't that type at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6762071 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 Not friendly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16153212 MR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 No, no she wasn't. Always had to be punctual. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6762071 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 When you were in the laundry did you have the same amount of time off or
 did you have different hours and times?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16153212 MR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 
Oh there we had - every evening off but you see I - we used to have a lot of washing, all the theatre and that, it was very hard but I always liked washing and ironing. And after I got home you see after fathe
r died I done it. I - I still do a few little pieces you know. Me - me smalls and that because - laundry's very dear now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6762071 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 
Were you supervised in the laundry, did you have somebody over you telling you what to do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16153212 MR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 Well - well there was the old - 
there was an older woman, well we just had to - wash and iron and had a big drying room, it was pretty hard work but I always - I never minded that. Well then when I got home you see I used to go out and do a little bit of - for pay, that was one and six 
a day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6762071 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 And you just got your dinner you told me?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16153212 MR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 
No, I don't, if I got me dinner but if I went half a day I got ninepence and no dinner. No, the most I ever earned was - was - well - now - I used to go to the Waterhouses when they had company and
 make the beds and wait at table and all that and I - I used to - clean the silver and the brass and I used to have to - I used to keep account but I never cheated the old lady. Sixpence and hour and she used to pay me once a month, well that wasn't too b
ad, that's the most -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6762071 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 That was sixpence an hour?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16153212 MR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 Yes, that's the most I ever earned.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6762071 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 What sort of work was that?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16153212 MR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 
Waiting - at table when they had visitors and setting the table, they used to have a lot of tenants parties, getting teas and all that and - and - cleaning the silver and the brass and - that and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6762071 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 How did she treat you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16153212 MR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 
Oh ever so well, she used to grumble at me, 'cos I used to clean the bedrooms too much for her, she was a dear old lady. She used to say, you don't want to keep doing this. Well of course I did, I liked to keep tidy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6762071 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 Did she know your mother and your family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16153212 MR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 
Oh yes. Used to come - oh yes, oh well - during the war she run little whist drives for the soldiers, 'cos that was a prison, and t
here was the room - where they used to be underneath, I don't know, what did they call that, they come - they've closed it in now, and a big fireplace and that - didn't they used to have a wheel or something, there's a big room up the top. And doors were 
as thick as that. She used to - invite me and - a lot of girls of the same age and we had little whist drives. Oh yes, Used to have a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6773215\charrsid8475667 tea party}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667  about - once a week, and get that for the old girl. 'Cos her daughter was at home with her but she didn't do anything. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6762071 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 
Before you went to Saffron Waldon, what did you do - you didn't go there straight from school did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16153212 MR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 
No, I went day girl - at one and six a week for - a year for some - for a year or two, about a year, then day girl - a day - out for
 the day at another place, a builders. Retired builders and his daughter. I started at one and sixpence a week. I used to get such chapped hands from scrubbing the bricks I used to cry at night with it. Hard work never hurt me but you know honestly - 'cos
 
I'm not too bad now mind you I often feel I don't want to do nothing but I - up I get and do it. I'm going to - I hope - I hope I'm going to get out more this wintertime because I didn't go out for three months and I got this hip and - pain and I didn't k
now what to do. And know I had -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16153212 MR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 
Well before nine, and of course there was only an oil lamp and candles you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6762071 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 And so just say again they used to toll the bell in the morning?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16153212 MR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 No, at eight o'clock at night.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6762071 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 Not in the morning too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16153212 MR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 No, at eight o'clock at night for people to go to bed.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6762071 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 Because in the little book it said 4am at one time they done it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16153212 MR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 Well no, I don't now -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6762071 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 That wasn't in your time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16153212 MR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 Oh no, no. I suppose someone else found that out in the records.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6762071 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 What about do you remember them tolling for the day of the month?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16153212 MR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 
Yes, it was every day - every night at eight o'clock. It was a - the - what they called - they call - they called the church clerk then but now they call them the verger. And
 same as - this is the first of December it would go one. Tomorrow night it would go two. And on the last day thirty or thirty-first.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6762071 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 It would be thirty or thirty-one?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16153212 MR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 
Yes. And then they would start one again. And people they what - they used to
 go to bed then the older people. And - but the Queen's Diamond Jubilee I - we had a tea up in the old grammar school and a Punch and Judy show, and I took my youngest brother, he was about - probably three then - and he was so frightened I had to bring h
i
m out. That was the first Punch and Judy show we'd ever had and I was very sorry to miss it but he would be - and then we had a very nice china mug given us, beautifully engraved with - with - Queen - Victoria on, and I kept it and then - during the secon
d world war I helped once a week at a shop in Saffron Waldon selling - everything we could lay hands on for the British Red Cross and I took my mug. Or rather regret it now but still it was for a good cause. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6762071 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 Did you have you know everybody in the
 village there did they all go along, all the children to the grammar school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16153212 MR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 
Oh yes, all - all the children. And then I was going to tell you about another red letter day was our Sunday school }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6773215\charrsid8475667 feat}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 . In the summertime we all assembled outside the gra
mmar - this old grammar school, they called it the church house now 'cos it's next door to the church - and we marched down the road singing. And then we went to have - had to have a service in church. Then we had a tea. And then we went down to the newly
 
built grammar school where we - where you went that night, and we used - in front you know is a large drive, we used to run races. And had threepence you know and that for prizes and before we came home the baker - he used to bake a lot of big round buns.
 With a - showing a sweet top, and we all had a bun. Well that was a special treat that time of day. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6762071 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 That was Mr Fiddler was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16153212 MR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 No. No, that was Mr Webb, Fiddler was a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6773215\charrsid8475667 sweep}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 . 'Cos that time of day we had open grates, we had two sweeps in the
 village. And that M.P. Harvey you'll see on the nicknames, he had a curvature of the spine and that's why they called him that. Mm.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6762071 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 What about Spitharvey why was he called Spitharvey?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16153212 MR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 I can't make out. I wish I'd asked my mother that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6762071 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 And Fiddler Searle, why did they call him that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16153212 MR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 
Well - well 'cos they said - he used - you know when the women took the grain to the - they took it to his place to be done out with the flail as I told you, well we had a man do it was a little bit simple
. They called him Silly Will. And he - he - intimated to the people that he used to - take some of the - of the wheat, and which that time of day they didn't say stealing they said fiddling. So they called him Fiddler Searle.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6762071 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 Would they call him that to his face, you did once didn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16153212 MR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 
Oh we always - oh yes, he - I - I don't know if he knew what they called it, he was a - a - a very keen Salvationist and when he used to sweep the chimney he'd kneel down and he's say, if he knew he was going to 
die that night he wasn't afraid. He was one of them proper old Salvation Army, 'cos at the side of where they thrashed it there's a - a big room where they used to have a - Salvationists. But they haven't had any for many years now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6762071 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 Were there quite a few of them in the village at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16153212 MR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 Yes, there were. Very good - yes, there were. That's died down now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6762071 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 What about is Mouldy Wright?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16153212 MR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 
Well I can't - I don't know - I cannot fathom, I only know - well - a relation of of - theirs married my sister, I don't think he knew, he died two years ago so - I - can't ask him but I can't think however come to call him that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6762071 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 And Spiranday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16153212 MR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 Well - my mother never knew, she - no, she didn't know that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6762071 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 And is Dorkey Bacon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16153212 MR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 Porky B
acon, well - well he - he was a water diviner. He had a big board over he used to go out with a twig - and find water, because his name was Bacon I - they called - I was about - I - all the men prac - oh I think they'll all be dead now. I knew a great man
y of 'em.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6762071 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 What about Honey Joe Clarke?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16153212 MR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 
Well I can never make that out. I never knew him but I knew his widow and she used to come up and see me and my mother sometimes she was a - left a widow and she had her living by doing - what they called t
ailoring and - the big grammar school had boarders and she used to mend all the carpets and mattresses and that. But she was very poor. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6762071 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 Did she get any help from anywhere?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16153212 MR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 No no, only what she earnt and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6762071 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 She didn't get any parish relief of anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16153212 MR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 
No, no I don't - well - not to my knowledge. That wasn't much of that about was it - it was very little what they did have you know then. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6762071 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 Do you remember anybody getting anything at any time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16153212 MR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 Well I remember as a young g
irl someone asked me - to fetch - a parish relief and I can't think who it was she was ill. So I went up to the house and the man what pay out they call him - the relieving officer. And he gave me one and sixpence, and I brought back - I can't think who i
t
 was. And - then there used to be a baker from Quentin the shops got the name over now Mumford, he used to come there every Wednesday afternoon - and these people who were allowed the parish relief - gathered outside - there's a road to Wickham as you com
e just up here there's a road up there and you come by there's a caf\'e9, gathered outside there and the baker used to come from Quentin and they had a loaf of bread. That's all they had. It was awful.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6762071 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 Do you remember seeing them }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6773215\charrsid8475667 queuing}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667  there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16153212 MR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 Oh y
es, see 'em - oh, every Wednesday, they used - and they used to wear a sort of a thin - cloak or shawl, they were very bad off. And I - my father sister - sister's husband died, she got one little boy - and expecting another child and he had a throat infe
c
tion and did - and he died, and she was only allowed one and sixpence for the oldest boy after the other boy was born she had to keep herself and her boy. And - well they died - my aunt lived to be fairly old, I used to go and see her after mother and fat
her had died and then - neither of these two sons married and they both died, they're dead now but - she had to work hard. Well they worked very hard then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6762071 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 Do you remember anybody going into the workhouse?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16153212 MR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 Well - yes, I do, but you know they was 
brought up at a meeting last week, there were supposed to be two workhouses everywhere, and I said to Mr Brown. I said, well there was a type of workhouse - along of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}
Bury Water Lane{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. They were single rooms. And you know when a farmer - when a man - had - h
ad to give up work if he worked on the land same as my father did when he had - couldn't work any longer you have a house with the job, and you had to come out. Well they were single rooms along there, and they were let at six shillings a week, they used 
t
o go down there. But they were sold when a lot of the village was sold by the owners Shawgrove Hall I - I think it was just before the war ended, and there's a tablet on the wall there which no one - has I've ever known it's so old has been able to read, 
b
ut of course they sold 'em out and - some people bought two and some - you see, so - but I think that was a type of workhouse but families - some families used to shut up and go into the workhouse for the winter, and the man used to work - have to do work
, break stones and that you know. And - well - winters were very hard for people about here same as the bricklayers and that. Of course they work all winter now but they never did any work round when it was frosty or anything. Mm.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6762071 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 Do you actually remember a family going in for the winter?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16153212 MR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 I've known families go in, but not from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Newport{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, I knew one went in from Wickham Bonham. But - of course you see the - agricultural labourers they had a job all winter you see, in the wintertime it was thrashing
 - in the old days with his flail and then when they had the - steam the engine you see they - that was - that was - thrashing they could - could find something to do. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6762071 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 Did you ever visit anybody who'd gone into the workhouse?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16153212 MR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 No, never.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6762071 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 Did any children at Newport school come from the workhouse to school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16153212 MR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 No, not that I remember. No, I can't remember any.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6762071 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 Just thinking of these nicknames again, these ones - is it Cam or Calm?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16153212 MR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Cam{\*\xmlclose}
. Dai Cam was his name was Elijah they called him Dai and his uncle was named Tub Cam but how or what that - how it }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6773215\charrsid8475667 come about}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667  I don't know. I knew them both very well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6762071 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 What about Tom?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16153212 MR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 
Tom Fry did you say? I knew him 'cos he used to - his wife was asthmatic and I used to do - the wash
ing for her, and - I don't know how they come to call him that, but he was a - he was a - a bricklayer, he was out of work all winter. I always used - I used to fetch the washing, take it up for her, she was terrible }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6773215\charrsid8475667 asthmatic}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 .
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6762071 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 Did they have children?
