th - went to live in Waldon, he used to let Shelgrove Hall 'cos there was - one of the Pitts lived up there one time. And then there was a Lord Cardross lived there. And then Sir James Bailey, who was - Member of Parliament for Walworth in 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}London{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, he bough
t it. And he came down there, he had - three sons - and two or three daughters, and then he married - I think - I don't - he married I believe when he came or soon after he came. And she - she was a very nice lady. I can't remember - she had a sister come
 
sometimes, and then - in those days there was a Girls Friendly society. That was very strong here one time and we joined them when we was about eleven as candidates. And we used to meet every Saturday afternoon in this old grammar school, that's right at 
the church gates, and this Lady Bailey - used to come down, and she learned us all to knit - on steel pins mens socks, that's how I first come to knit.
