ed - whether they renewed it after the first world war but - oak apple day, the twenty-ninth of May. Which King Charles was supposed to - hid in oak tree. I know that much history. I disliked history, I wouldn't learn it. And - every morn - twenty-ninth o
f
 May - from the time I can remember there was a large bell oak of the front doorstep. And all we children had to put a piece in our buttonhole - before we went to school, if we didn't we got a kick. And then in the evening the bellringers did that, they u
sed to come round}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6773215\charrsid8475667  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10314666\charrsid8475667 
and receive a - coppers or whatever people liked to give 'em and - and - then they used to spend the evening - have the evening at the pub there used to be - well always six bellringers I don't know whether there was any more, and they had
 these hand bells I think we've got 'em here now but of course there's not the ringers about like there used to be. And plough Monday is the second Monday after Christmas. I don't think I might remember it vaguely but - the ploughmen they used to take a p
l
ough and go round the village and knock on the doors, and if they didn't give 'em any money they'd plough a little bit of the path up. Well then they was - they used to meet at night and chuck - share the money and then have a jolly evening. 'Cos there wa
s
n't much for the men to do. But there was also a young mens club which the curate - our old vicar was old, and had a curate, the Reverend Thomson, there was a young mens club where my brothers used to go - every night. There's a little - sort of one room 
in the high street attached to the cottage and they used to go in there. And play games and that. They didn't pay very much and he used to give 'em a very good supper he wasn't married every - once a year. And there was that for the younger people. Mm.

